1
00:00:04,171 --> 00:00:07,239
The red light's on.
That means we're ready, yeah?

2
00:00:07,307 --> 00:00:08,774
(man)
Yes.

3
00:00:08,841 --> 00:00:13,277
Would you tell us why and how
a psychic becomes a CBI agent?

4
00:00:13,345 --> 00:00:16,827
I'm not a psychic.
No such things as psychics.

5
00:00:16,895 --> 00:00:18,823
And he's not a CBI agent.
He's a consultant.

6
00:00:19,191 --> 00:00:21,175
Big difference.

7
00:00:21,243 --> 00:00:24,031
"no such thing as psychics."
uh, care to elaborate?

8
00:00:29,838 --> 00:00:31,789
Uh, no, not particularly.

9
00:00:31,857 --> 00:00:34,985
Um, you know what?
This--this is not--

10
00:00:35,053 --> 00:00:37,269
This is not a good idea,
I don't think.

11
00:00:37,337 --> 00:00:40,228
Um, it's not a good idea.

12
00:00:40,296 --> 00:00:42,076
(clears throat)
Okay.

13
00:00:42,144 --> 00:00:44,560
Um, maybe we'll--
we'll come back to that later.

14
00:00:44,634 --> 00:00:46,781
Uh, how do your cases
usually start?

15
00:00:46,849 --> 00:00:49,555
Uh, a case begins with us
getting a phone call

16
00:00:49,622 --> 00:00:52,535
from the A.G.'s office
to lead an investigation.

17
00:00:52,603 --> 00:00:55,451
In the St. Clare homicide,
the local D.A. wanted us on it

18
00:00:55,519 --> 00:00:57,462
because there were
political issues involved.

19
00:00:57,530 --> 00:00:59,473
And how did
the local cops feel

20
00:00:59,540 --> 00:01:01,583
bout your--
your team coming in?

21
00:01:01,651 --> 00:01:05,368
We get along extremely well
with our local partners

22
00:01:05,435 --> 00:01:07,643
in law enforcement, yeah.

23
00:01:07,714 --> 00:01:09,651
My people can handle this,
no problem.

24
00:01:09,722 --> 00:01:12,564
California Bureau
of Interference is what you are.

25
00:01:12,632 --> 00:01:14,944
Interference? That's witty.
Stay out of this.

26
00:01:15,012 --> 00:01:17,354
I'm sure your people are
competent, Chief Donner.

27
00:01:17,421 --> 00:01:19,363
We're simply following
the A.G.'s orders.

28
00:01:19,430 --> 00:01:22,008
Screw the A.G.. This case is
going to be in the news,

29
00:01:22,076 --> 00:01:23,882
and you people are
spotlight hogs. That's all.

30
00:01:23,950 --> 00:01:24,866
I assure you, chief--

31
00:01:24,867 --> 00:01:27,467
Don't waste your time. His anger
runs deeper than you can reach.

32
00:01:28,034 --> 00:01:29,974
Seriously,
don't start trouble here.

33
00:01:30,041 --> 00:01:31,982
It's the last thing
we need.

34
00:01:32,050 --> 00:01:33,823
The victim is
Martha St. Clare, 34--

35
00:01:33,891 --> 00:01:36,464
Media relations coordinator
for the mayor of this town.

36
00:01:36,532 --> 00:01:38,940
Mayor was here to break ground
on a new development,

37
00:01:39,007 --> 00:01:41,244
Dug up her P.R. flack instead.
Ouch.

38
00:01:41,312 --> 00:01:42,285
Yeah, victim was stabbed
twice in the chest,

39
00:01:42,286 --> 00:01:43,286
But there's no blood here.

40
00:01:43,752 --> 00:01:45,023
Killed elsewhere.

41
00:01:45,090 --> 00:01:47,762
Home. Her nails are done.
Her hair's done.

42
00:01:47,832 --> 00:01:50,870
This woman doesn't wear
sweatpants anywhere but at home.

43
00:01:50,938 --> 00:01:54,209
Cho, have Van Pelt
check it out.

44
00:01:55,976 --> 00:01:57,785
The killer wanted the body
to be discovered here

45
00:01:57,854 --> 00:02:00,125
under the glare
of the cameras.

46
00:02:00,193 --> 00:02:02,866
And likely came here
to watch the fuss.

47
00:02:02,934 --> 00:02:05,706
Likely.
Maybe the camera crews
caught something.

48
00:02:05,774 --> 00:02:07,080
We'll need to have them
look into it.

49
00:02:07,081 --> 00:02:08,081
(sniffing)

50
00:02:08,748 --> 00:02:10,187
There's bruises on her arms.

51
00:02:10,255 --> 00:02:12,062
Looks like something
was ripped off her neck

52
00:02:12,130 --> 00:02:15,236
during the struggle.
Is he sniffing her?

53
00:02:15,304 --> 00:02:18,277
Yes.
You pay him to sniff people?

54
00:02:18,345 --> 00:02:21,384
Apparently.
She's been smoking.

55
00:02:21,452 --> 00:02:25,056
The nicotine patch on her arm
says she was trying to quit.

56
00:02:25,124 --> 00:02:28,261
So under stress of late.
Well, case closed.

57
00:02:28,629 --> 00:02:30,402
Stress got a knife
and stabbed her to death.

58
00:02:30,470 --> 00:02:33,806
He's on a roll.
You're on a roll.

59
00:02:33,874 --> 00:02:36,646
(sniffs) Cheap soap.
Unironed shirt. Stomach pains.

60
00:02:36,714 --> 00:02:39,219
Recent loss of weight. I'm gonna
take a wild guess here.

61
00:02:39,287 --> 00:02:41,693
You're angry and unhappy
'cause you're living in a motel

62
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:43,397
because your wife found out
about the woman

63
00:02:43,465 --> 00:02:45,002
you're having an affair with
that you don't even care for.

64
00:02:45,270 --> 00:02:47,408
You're a seething mass
of self-loathing,

65
00:02:47,476 --> 00:02:48,783
And understandably so.

66
00:02:50,084 --> 00:02:51,584
You son of a bitch!

67
00:02:51,651 --> 00:02:54,657
Chief Donner, my apologies.
He was completely out of line.

68
00:02:55,525 --> 00:02:59,630
Let--let's just get back
to the body. Sir?

69
00:03:00,599 --> 00:03:05,340
<font color=#7FFF00>♫ The Mentalist 2x12 ♫</font>
<font color=#FF0000>Bleeding Heart</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>Original Air Date on January 21, 2009</font>

70
00:03:05,408 --> 00:03:09,412
-- Sync, corrected by <font color="#00ff00">elderman</font> --
-- for <font color="#ffff00">addicted.com</font> --

71
00:03:11,066 --> 00:03:13,500
We've closed more cases
than any other unit in the CBI,

72
00:03:13,568 --> 00:03:15,502
But we don't keep score
that way.

73
00:03:15,570 --> 00:03:17,370
It's not a contest.

74
00:03:18,238 --> 00:03:20,372
And you--you also lead

75
00:03:20,440 --> 00:03:23,742
in the number of complaints
and lawsuits filed.

76
00:03:24,845 --> 00:03:28,079
Okay, hold it.

77
00:03:28,146 --> 00:03:30,648
I thought we had an agreement.

78
00:03:32,116 --> 00:03:34,217
Brenda, a word.

79
00:03:38,987 --> 00:03:41,590
(lowers voice) Jane's right.
This isn't a good idea.

80
00:03:41,657 --> 00:03:44,192
I thought this was supposed
to be positive coverage.

81
00:03:44,260 --> 00:03:46,995
It is! It will be. If we're open
and honest about the issues,

82
00:03:47,062 --> 00:03:49,430
The positivity follows.
That's P.R. 101.

83
00:03:49,498 --> 00:03:52,132
We're trying to solve
a woman's murder here, Brenda.

84
00:03:52,200 --> 00:03:54,368
We don't have time
to waste on P.R.

85
00:03:54,436 --> 00:03:57,103
Teresa, you know that we have
been crucified by the media

86
00:03:57,171 --> 00:03:59,439
ever since Bosco
and his team were killed

87
00:03:59,506 --> 00:04:03,474
here in our own house. When KTQZ
asked me for access yesterday,

88
00:04:03,542 --> 00:04:06,411
I jumped at it,
and the deputy A.G. concurred.

89
00:04:08,478 --> 00:04:09,580
Who is this guy anyway?

90
00:04:09,947 --> 00:04:12,248
Totally legit
TV investigative reporter.

91
00:04:12,249 --> 00:04:13,249
Mike Brewster.

92
00:04:13,315 --> 00:04:15,952
He has been covering
the central valley for years.

93
00:04:17,520 --> 00:04:19,787
We need this, Teresa.
Please.

94
00:04:19,955 --> 00:04:21,889
Work with us.
He stays out of my way.

95
00:04:21,957 --> 00:04:24,458
He can film in the office
and in the bullpen,

96
00:04:24,525 --> 00:04:26,393
But not out in the field.
Thank you.

97
00:04:27,260 --> 00:04:28,794
Seriously, thank you.

98
00:04:29,162 --> 00:04:31,864
You won't be sorry. And it's
a two-way street, Agent Lisbon.

99
00:04:31,931 --> 00:04:33,134
If there's anything
I can do for you...

100
00:04:34,135 --> 00:04:35,135
There is one thing.

101
00:04:36,201 --> 00:04:38,136
Okay, so this is the footage
Steve and I grabbed

102
00:04:38,203 --> 00:04:39,204
of the groundbreaking.

103
00:04:39,271 --> 00:04:42,473
That's the Mayor--
Melba Walker Shannon.

104
00:04:42,540 --> 00:04:44,641
She plays up the folksy image,

105
00:04:44,709 --> 00:04:45,777
But she can be tough as nails
if she needs to be.

106
00:04:45,778 --> 00:04:47,978
Nice shoes. Chip?

107
00:04:48,145 --> 00:04:50,080
No, thanks. Who's the rich guy
next to the mayor?

108
00:04:50,081 --> 00:04:52,381
Oh, that's Heaton Krupp.
He's the private developer

109
00:04:52,448 --> 00:04:53,316
On the project--

110
00:04:53,317 --> 00:04:54,817
off the record, a prize jerk.

111
00:04:54,918 --> 00:04:56,018
Who are those people?

112
00:04:56,083 --> 00:04:58,351
Tree huggers.
The project's going up

113
00:04:58,419 --> 00:04:59,887
on the edge
of some reclaimed land.

114
00:04:59,888 --> 00:05:01,688
You mean protected wildlands.

115
00:05:01,855 --> 00:05:02,955
You say "potato."

116
00:05:02,956 --> 00:05:05,056
You have any other footage
of the crowds?

117
00:05:05,023 --> 00:05:07,124
Not really.
Other networks might,

118
00:05:07,192 --> 00:05:08,395
But gaining access
can be tricky.

119
00:05:08,396 --> 00:05:09,996
It'd be good to get
a different perspective.

120
00:05:10,163 --> 00:05:11,996
Cho, see if you can
get the footage.
You got it.

121
00:05:12,064 --> 00:05:15,166
All right,
that's Wilson Fonteneau,

122
00:05:15,233 --> 00:05:18,869
The mayor's flunky,
and here comes the money shot.

123
00:05:29,077 --> 00:05:30,245
Whew.

124
00:05:33,782 --> 00:05:35,716
(click)

125
00:05:35,783 --> 00:05:37,716
These are
from the victim's home.

126
00:05:37,784 --> 00:05:39,719
Besides the signs
of a scuffle,

127
00:05:39,787 --> 00:05:42,553
the only thing that seemed to be
missing was the victim's laptop.

128
00:05:42,621 --> 00:05:47,022
The murderer probably took it.
Check out this necklace.

129
00:05:47,089 --> 00:05:50,658
From the photos, it looks
like she wore it a lot.

130
00:05:50,725 --> 00:05:52,061
You think it could have
made the mark on her neck?

131
00:05:52,062 --> 00:05:53,862
Could be. When you go
to the apartment,

132
00:05:54,129 --> 00:05:57,063
do a targeted search.
The necklace is long gone.

133
00:05:57,131 --> 00:06:00,399
My guess--the killer
made a souvenir of it.
Go.

134
00:06:00,467 --> 00:06:02,467
Okay.
Where we going?

135
00:06:02,535 --> 00:06:04,536
Mayor's office.

136
00:06:06,104 --> 00:06:08,672
I don't have any problem
being in charge, no.

137
00:06:08,739 --> 00:06:12,409
I mean, maybe at first
for a while,

138
00:06:12,476 --> 00:06:14,111
as a woman, it was a challenge,

139
00:06:14,179 --> 00:06:15,780
but the demands
of the job take over.

140
00:06:15,847 --> 00:06:17,047
Yeah.

141
00:06:17,915 --> 00:06:19,049
(man) Tell me
about your weekends.

142
00:06:20,116 --> 00:06:21,484
You want to know what I do
on my weekends?

143
00:06:21,552 --> 00:06:22,653
Yeah.

144
00:06:23,721 --> 00:06:25,388
Why do you want to know that?

145
00:06:26,655 --> 00:06:30,093
I mean, I have no problem having
a life, if that's what you mean.

146
00:06:30,160 --> 00:06:32,661
I don't know why anybody
would say otherwise--

147
00:06:32,729 --> 00:06:34,630
If they do say otherwise.

148
00:06:34,697 --> 00:06:36,531
Um, I'm sorry.

149
00:06:36,598 --> 00:06:38,332
What were we talking about?

150
00:06:48,337 --> 00:06:49,471
Sorry for the delay.

151
00:06:49,539 --> 00:06:51,173
The mayor's just finishing up
another meeting.

152
00:06:51,241 --> 00:06:53,210
It's been a crazy day
around here. Can I help you?

153
00:06:53,277 --> 00:06:55,644
Oh, no, I'm fine. Thanks.

154
00:06:55,712 --> 00:06:59,380
Mr. Fonteneau, did you work
closely with Martha St. Clare?

155
00:06:59,448 --> 00:07:02,916
For 16 months.
Martha hired me, actually.

156
00:07:02,984 --> 00:07:05,218
We noticed in a lot
of recent photographs

157
00:07:05,286 --> 00:07:08,687
that she had a-a necklace on
with a beautiful stone.

158
00:07:08,754 --> 00:07:11,591
Yes, a topaz, I think.
It was her birthstone.

159
00:07:11,659 --> 00:07:14,661
She got it Christmas of last
year and never took it off.

160
00:07:14,662 --> 00:07:15,862
Do you know who gave it to her?

161
00:07:16,229 --> 00:07:19,164
No.
She had a lot of meetings,
even on weekends--

162
00:07:19,232 --> 00:07:21,100
Business interests,
community groups, book club.

163
00:07:21,167 --> 00:07:23,101
Tomorrow is a big day.
She has a star

164
00:07:23,169 --> 00:07:26,570
and 3 exclamation marks
at 11:00.

165
00:07:26,538 --> 00:07:27,471
Yes.

166
00:07:27,639 --> 00:07:30,741
Uh, she scheduled a briefing
with the city council.

167
00:07:30,809 --> 00:07:31,878
On what subject?

168
00:07:31,879 --> 00:07:34,679
I don't know, to be honest.
The mayor will know.

169
00:07:34,746 --> 00:07:36,513
Was she dating anyone?

170
00:07:37,581 --> 00:07:39,415
A social life--Martha?

171
00:07:39,483 --> 00:07:41,384
No, she had a cat.

172
00:07:41,452 --> 00:07:42,819
Ah. Yes. See?

173
00:07:43,587 --> 00:07:45,121
But it died.
Right.

174
00:07:46,789 --> 00:07:48,523
Excuse me.
Are you the CBI Agents?

175
00:07:48,591 --> 00:07:49,826
Mayor,
thank you for seeing us.

176
00:07:49,894 --> 00:07:51,995
Happy to help,
and please call me Melba.

177
00:07:52,096 --> 00:07:53,296
Like the toast?

178
00:07:53,363 --> 00:07:55,131
Just like. This way.

179
00:08:01,436 --> 00:08:04,137
Can you tell us about
your construction project

180
00:08:04,205 --> 00:08:06,138
that you were
opening yesterday?

181
00:08:06,206 --> 00:08:08,936
It's the Granton Complex, yes.
We are very proud of it.

182
00:08:09,204 --> 00:08:12,137
It's office and retail space
plus housing,

183
00:08:12,204 --> 00:08:14,840
all built with
the latest green technology.

184
00:08:14,907 --> 00:08:17,475
And what was Martha's
involvement in the project?

185
00:08:17,543 --> 00:08:19,744
None, really. She...

186
00:08:20,812 --> 00:08:22,713
She was my media liaison.

187
00:08:22,781 --> 00:08:26,116
She was not engaged
in policy issues.

188
00:08:26,183 --> 00:08:30,086
Then what was she gonna talk
about at city council tomorrow?

189
00:08:30,154 --> 00:08:34,356
Oh, a press junket.
It was river rafting, I believe.

190
00:08:34,424 --> 00:08:36,825
Chief Donner says your office

191
00:08:36,826 --> 00:08:37,826
has received several threats
from environmental activists.

192
00:08:39,895 --> 00:08:41,829
Activists?
No, they're terrorists.

193
00:08:41,897 --> 00:08:44,999
They burned down vacation condos
up on the mountain.

194
00:08:45,066 --> 00:08:47,701
They destroyed luxury car lots
just one town over.

195
00:08:47,769 --> 00:08:51,404
They're led by a madman,
and he calls himself Jasper.

196
00:08:51,472 --> 00:08:54,206
Excuse me.

197
00:08:55,874 --> 00:08:57,609
Wilson,
anything else can wait.

198
00:09:04,181 --> 00:09:05,115
The threats?

199
00:09:05,183 --> 00:09:07,050
Yes. Um...

200
00:09:10,787 --> 00:09:14,690
<i>(voice distorted) the Granton
development is an abomination--</i>

201
00:09:14,758 --> 00:09:18,593
<i>A hundred acres
of pristine wildlands razed,</i>

202
00:09:18,761 --> 00:09:20,962
<i>An entire ecosystem endangered.</i>

203
00:09:21,329 --> 00:09:22,797
<i>It must stop.</i>

204
00:09:22,865 --> 00:09:25,834
<i>It will stop, no matter
what needs to be done.</i>

205
00:09:25,902 --> 00:09:30,937
<i>My name is Jasper,
and I am legion.</i>

206
00:09:31,005 --> 00:09:34,872
(chuckling) Come on.

207
00:09:34,939 --> 00:09:36,840
"I am legion."
that's just silly.

208
00:09:37,108 --> 00:09:38,343
Silly?
Yeah.

209
00:09:38,810 --> 00:09:41,079
He murdered Martha.
Well, you assume.

210
00:09:41,147 --> 00:09:44,083
Yes, I do. The body was buried
at the site, for God's sake.

211
00:09:44,152 --> 00:09:46,720
And that is a clear message,
isn't it?

212
00:09:46,788 --> 00:09:49,055
Melba,
why would he kill Martha...

213
00:09:49,123 --> 00:09:51,991
and not kill you?

214
00:09:52,058 --> 00:09:53,992
It'd be
a bigger publicity coup.

215
00:09:55,060 --> 00:09:56,360
Excuse me?

216
00:09:56,428 --> 00:09:59,930
Uh...
What Mr. Jane is trying to ask
is whether there was somebody

217
00:09:59,998 --> 00:10:02,566
with a more direct personal
grudge against Martha.
Mm...

218
00:10:02,634 --> 00:10:05,068
Yeah.
No.

219
00:10:05,135 --> 00:10:08,103
She was a lovely--
was a lovely person.

220
00:10:08,171 --> 00:10:10,138
Oh, then why did you
dislike her so much?

221
00:10:10,606 --> 00:10:12,040
I didn't dislike Martha.

222
00:10:12,607 --> 00:10:15,942
Why would I employ someone
that I don't like?

223
00:10:16,309 --> 00:10:17,577
That's a very good question.
When you said it,

224
00:10:17,645 --> 00:10:20,179
Your jaw tensed and your eyes
went empty like a cobra.

225
00:10:20,180 --> 00:10:21,180
Wilson!

226
00:10:21,647 --> 00:10:22,648
I'm not saying
you killed her.

227
00:10:22,815 --> 00:10:24,351
I'm just saying that you're
relieved that she's dead.

228
00:10:24,352 --> 00:10:26,152
These people
will be leaving now.

229
00:10:26,518 --> 00:10:28,553
Oh, I like the way you say that,
Melba-like-the-toast--

230
00:10:28,621 --> 00:10:30,589
So tough and commanding.
Let me tell you something.

231
00:10:30,656 --> 00:10:33,224
We are state law enforcement,
and we leave

232
00:10:33,291 --> 00:10:33,994
when we want to leave.

233
00:10:33,995 --> 00:10:35,095
(Lisbon)
Thank you for your time.

234
00:10:35,161 --> 00:10:36,663
(Patrick)
She wants to leave.

235
00:10:38,664 --> 00:10:39,664
See yah.

236
00:10:43,901 --> 00:10:45,401
You blew my cool.

237
00:10:45,468 --> 00:10:47,870
I swear, sometimes I think
you need medication.

238
00:10:47,937 --> 00:10:48,938
It's like you've got
A.D.D. or something.

239
00:10:49,405 --> 00:10:51,806
Well, "A," I'm not so sure
that A.D.D. even exists,

240
00:10:51,874 --> 00:10:53,908
and "B," I was winding her up
for a reason.

241
00:10:53,909 --> 00:10:54,909
Which is?

242
00:10:55,076 --> 00:10:57,044
A diversion.
The message the aide brought in

243
00:10:57,112 --> 00:10:58,546
Made her nervous,
so I took it.

244
00:10:58,547 --> 00:10:59,547
You're stealing now?

245
00:10:59,614 --> 00:11:00,481
Well, let's just
call it purloining.

246
00:11:01,482 --> 00:11:02,282
What does it say?

247
00:11:02,349 --> 00:11:06,251
It says "your 3:00 meeting
has now been moved to 3:15."

248
00:11:06,318 --> 00:11:07,052
I'm just kidding.

249
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:10,588
It says, "9-1-1. Call now.
Urgent. About Martha."

250
00:11:10,655 --> 00:11:12,456
From Heaton Krupp.

251
00:11:12,524 --> 00:11:15,659
The developer
of the Granton project.

252
00:11:16,727 --> 00:11:18,128
Oh, yeah.

253
00:11:18,196 --> 00:11:20,129
(man) Do you enjoy
police work?

254
00:11:20,197 --> 00:11:22,198
Mm...

255
00:11:27,068 --> 00:11:28,068
Patrick?

256
00:11:28,536 --> 00:11:29,770
Uh, yeah, I'm thinking.

257
00:11:29,838 --> 00:11:33,006
Uh, mm, yes and no.

258
00:11:33,074 --> 00:11:37,042
Uh, yeah, sometimes.
Sometimes not.

259
00:11:38,110 --> 00:11:39,111
Forget it, Steve.

260
00:11:41,178 --> 00:11:42,879
Why do you so dislike
being filmed?

261
00:11:42,947 --> 00:11:44,981
Uh... (clears throat)

262
00:11:46,049 --> 00:11:47,549
'cause you're
stealing my soul.

263
00:11:51,018 --> 00:11:52,919
So I called the mayor.
So what?

264
00:11:53,386 --> 00:11:55,721
I'm building a $20 million
complex in her town.

265
00:11:55,788 --> 00:11:58,522
I call her a lot.
About ms. St. Clare?

266
00:11:57,890 --> 00:12:00,525
About when I can start
construction again.

267
00:12:01,593 --> 00:12:03,461
This is costing me hundreds
of thousands of dollars.

268
00:12:03,529 --> 00:12:05,200
It cost ms. St. Clare
a lot more.

269
00:12:05,501 --> 00:12:07,301
And I'm sorry about that.

270
00:12:07,768 --> 00:12:09,907
I am. But there's nothing
I can do about it.

271
00:12:11,375 --> 00:12:13,310
Martha would have
wanted us to go on.

272
00:12:13,378 --> 00:12:14,946
You knew her well enough
to know that?

273
00:12:14,947 --> 00:12:17,047
You're right. I'm being pious.

274
00:12:17,914 --> 00:12:19,382
Maybe Martha would have said,
"screw it."

275
00:12:20,249 --> 00:12:21,451
I knew her not at all
outside of business.

276
00:12:21,452 --> 00:12:22,652
Really?

277
00:12:23,419 --> 00:12:24,520
'cause we just got
her cell phone records,

278
00:12:24,587 --> 00:12:26,288
and you called her
ten times yesterday.

279
00:12:26,656 --> 00:12:27,190
You want to tell us
what you wanted

280
00:12:27,258 --> 00:12:28,259
To talk about so urgently?

281
00:12:28,360 --> 00:12:30,460
Seems I should get my lawyer,
have him sit in with us.

282
00:12:30,426 --> 00:12:31,928
Sure. That's your right.

283
00:12:31,929 --> 00:12:33,929
Tell him to bring all your
permits for the Granton project.

284
00:12:34,096 --> 00:12:35,330
My permits? Why?
Why not?

285
00:12:35,498 --> 00:12:36,866
And we should make sure this
stays an active crime scene--

286
00:12:36,933 --> 00:12:38,435
Keep everyone out
until the case is solved.

287
00:12:38,436 --> 00:12:39,436
Could take weeks.

288
00:12:39,602 --> 00:12:43,003
See... we were talking
about money, okay?

289
00:12:43,471 --> 00:12:45,805
$10 million in public funds
was to be released

290
00:12:45,873 --> 00:12:49,141
When we broke ground. Then I
heard rumors that St. Clare

291
00:12:49,209 --> 00:12:51,477
was planning to tell the city
council to withhold them.

292
00:12:51,478 --> 00:12:52,478
Why?

293
00:12:52,545 --> 00:12:55,380
I don't know! I mean, that's
what I was trying to find out.

294
00:12:55,381 --> 00:12:56,781
But St. Clare was killed

295
00:12:56,848 --> 00:12:58,015
before she could talk
to the city council.

296
00:12:58,016 --> 00:12:58,916
Yes, but--

297
00:12:58,983 --> 00:13:00,251
So the $10 million will
come to you after all.

298
00:13:00,252 --> 00:13:01,652
What are you--are you
trying to lay this on me?

299
00:13:01,718 --> 00:13:04,586
Because you're messing
with the wrong guy, officer!

300
00:13:04,587 --> 00:13:06,387
We're not officers.
We're Agents.

301
00:13:06,454 --> 00:13:08,555
That's quite a temper
you got there.
(glass shatters)

302
00:13:09,122 --> 00:13:10,122
Look out!

303
00:13:10,525 --> 00:13:14,028
(grunts)
get down, get down!
Get on the floor!

304
00:13:14,096 --> 00:13:17,097
Help!
(shouting indistinctly)

305
00:13:17,165 --> 00:13:20,132
I got the door!
Go, go, go, go!

306
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:22,601
I got the door!
(grunting)

307
00:13:22,668 --> 00:13:26,137
Aah! I got you.

308
00:13:29,441 --> 00:13:30,775
(glass shatters)

309
00:13:34,946 --> 00:13:36,213
(coughs)

310
00:13:45,505 --> 00:13:48,339
(all coughing and wheezing)

311
00:14:04,686 --> 00:14:06,455
This was done by someone who
knew what he or she was doing.

312
00:14:07,423 --> 00:14:09,356
(coughing)
crackpot Jasper.

313
00:14:09,424 --> 00:14:10,657
He's a terrorist,

314
00:14:10,725 --> 00:14:13,261
And you ain't doing jack
to catch him, chief.

315
00:14:14,530 --> 00:14:16,466
I'm in charge of the town
of Salter, Mr. Krupp,

316
00:14:17,533 --> 00:14:18,467
not the outlying areas.

317
00:14:18,735 --> 00:14:20,401
(indistinct
police radio chatter)

318
00:14:20,469 --> 00:14:23,004
Jasper's never launched
an attack here in town before.

319
00:14:23,005 --> 00:14:24,005
Until now.

320
00:14:24,372 --> 00:14:26,973
Hey! Check this out.

321
00:14:33,580 --> 00:14:36,314
Apparently, this is
the same tag that Jasper used

322
00:14:36,382 --> 00:14:39,550
in the attack on the condos.

323
00:14:41,119 --> 00:14:43,887
It's good just here?
(man) that's great.

324
00:14:43,954 --> 00:14:45,888
Uh, I've been in fires before.

325
00:14:45,956 --> 00:14:49,259
I worked with the, uh,
arson squad in San Diego

326
00:14:49,327 --> 00:14:52,028
for a couple years, so I'm not
unfamiliar with the issues.

327
00:14:52,095 --> 00:14:54,563
It's never pleasant, though.
(chuckles)

328
00:14:54,631 --> 00:14:56,564
Um, I mean, when you're--

329
00:14:56,632 --> 00:14:59,233
When you're in it, it's--
there's no time to think.

330
00:14:59,301 --> 00:15:02,538
But--but afterwards,
well...

331
00:15:02,606 --> 00:15:04,907
Yeah.

332
00:15:04,975 --> 00:15:06,909
It can make you think.

333
00:15:06,977 --> 00:15:09,444
There was a...

334
00:15:09,512 --> 00:15:13,114
There was a moment there
where, uh...

335
00:15:16,417 --> 00:15:20,019
Yeah, makes you think.

336
00:15:21,655 --> 00:15:23,923
It's a gift, isn't it?

337
00:15:23,991 --> 00:15:25,525
Life.

338
00:15:25,592 --> 00:15:29,128
You should be
grateful for it...

339
00:15:29,195 --> 00:15:32,430
Make the most of it.

340
00:15:32,498 --> 00:15:34,567
We have to catch this guy
before he kills someone else.

341
00:15:34,568 --> 00:15:36,068
He hasn't killed anyone yet.

342
00:15:36,334 --> 00:15:38,234
Not Martha St. Clare?

343
00:15:38,302 --> 00:15:40,603
Eh.
Martha St. Clare was about
to stall the development.

344
00:15:40,671 --> 00:15:43,106
That exactly what Jasper wants.
So why kill her?

345
00:15:43,174 --> 00:15:45,776
(Lisbon) Maybe he didn't
know Martha's intentions.

346
00:15:45,844 --> 00:15:48,611
But the mayor must have known.
Let's go see her.

347
00:15:48,678 --> 00:15:51,612
Yeah. You guys look
into this Jasper character.

348
00:15:51,680 --> 00:15:52,882
Don't bother.
He's a red herring.

349
00:15:52,883 --> 00:15:54,883
What does that mean, anyway--
a red herring?

350
00:15:54,949 --> 00:15:56,383
A red herring is
what you look in to

351
00:15:56,451 --> 00:15:58,385
regardless of what
Jane tells you.

352
00:15:58,453 --> 00:16:00,355
Anything on
the networks' footage?

353
00:16:00,356 --> 00:16:01,556
They've been
throwing up hurdles--

354
00:16:01,623 --> 00:16:02,992
Something about
first amendment issues.

355
00:16:02,993 --> 00:16:05,393
Get the footage. I'm tired
of hearing their excuses.

356
00:16:05,560 --> 00:16:09,262
We I.D. Somebody in the crowd,
maybe we get lucky.
Yes, boss.

357
00:16:09,329 --> 00:16:11,464
Why am I a detective?
Why are you a reporter?

358
00:16:11,532 --> 00:16:11,901
What?

359
00:16:12,568 --> 00:16:13,736
Why are you making
this documentary?

360
00:16:13,737 --> 00:16:15,937
It's a fresh perspective
on law enforcement.

361
00:16:16,003 --> 00:16:17,404
No, I mean,
what's in it for you?

362
00:16:18,072 --> 00:16:21,006
Well, uh, scoring this exclusive
is a good way to get noticed.

363
00:16:21,074 --> 00:16:23,975
So you're ambitious. How long
you been doing the news here?

364
00:16:24,042 --> 00:16:26,010
About eight years.
Anchor?

365
00:16:26,077 --> 00:16:27,146
Mostly fieldwork.

366
00:16:27,147 --> 00:16:28,947
So you're ambitious, but you
haven't gotten very far.

367
00:16:30,413 --> 00:16:32,946
I, uh, I guess
that's about it, yeah.

368
00:16:33,012 --> 00:16:34,913
You don't like being asked
questions, do you?

369
00:16:34,980 --> 00:16:37,815
The team as a whole seems
to have a problem with that.

370
00:16:37,883 --> 00:16:40,316
Is that a question?

371
00:16:40,383 --> 00:16:42,851
Mike, if I can interrupt here?
Yeah.

372
00:16:42,919 --> 00:16:44,819
We're clear.

373
00:16:44,887 --> 00:16:48,922
Uh, there's coffee in
the kitchen, John. I'm so sorry.

374
00:16:48,989 --> 00:16:50,356
Agent Cho?

375
00:16:50,424 --> 00:16:51,824
Yeah?

376
00:16:51,892 --> 00:16:53,827
It is the specific request
of the deputy A.G.

377
00:16:53,894 --> 00:16:56,862
that your unit cooperate
fully with the media.

378
00:16:56,930 --> 00:16:59,331
What's your point?
(coughs)

379
00:16:59,399 --> 00:17:01,466
(Rigsby clears throat)

380
00:17:01,534 --> 00:17:03,468
Ohh.

381
00:17:03,536 --> 00:17:05,536
(Rigsby coughs)

382
00:17:11,875 --> 00:17:14,143
Mayor Shannon,
we need to talk.

383
00:17:14,210 --> 00:17:16,878
Of course. I have a meeting.
Please make it fast.

384
00:17:16,946 --> 00:17:20,982
Sure. How big was your bribe
from Heaton Krupp?

385
00:17:21,049 --> 00:17:24,118
That is
an outrageous slander.

386
00:17:24,186 --> 00:17:26,720
You sold your approval
of the Granton project.

387
00:17:26,788 --> 00:17:28,721
Martha found out.
She was gonna reveal it

388
00:17:28,789 --> 00:17:31,724
At the city council meeting,
which you said was gonna be

389
00:17:31,791 --> 00:17:34,559
about river rafting,
of all things.

390
00:17:34,626 --> 00:17:36,560
River rafting--
from where did you pull that?

391
00:17:36,628 --> 00:17:38,828
You better have
really good personal lawyers.

392
00:17:38,896 --> 00:17:41,864
If you pursue
this absurd line of harassment,

393
00:17:41,932 --> 00:17:44,369
I will hang you by your heels.

394
00:17:44,370 --> 00:17:46,470
Did you get a slice, too,
or are you strictly wage labor?

395
00:17:46,536 --> 00:17:49,538
I--
your superiors will hear
from our lawyers.

396
00:17:49,606 --> 00:17:50,373
Oh,
don't bother with lawyers.

397
00:17:50,441 --> 00:17:51,775
It's such a waste
of taxpayer dollars.

398
00:17:51,843 --> 00:17:53,311
Just confess.
You'll feel a lot better.

399
00:17:53,312 --> 00:17:56,812
In actuality, you have no proof
of this so-called bribery.

400
00:17:56,879 --> 00:17:57,880
Uh, none at all.

401
00:17:59,947 --> 00:18:02,315
Are all CBI Agents
this incompetent?

402
00:18:02,383 --> 00:18:05,251
Have you even bothered to check
her lover as a suspect?

403
00:18:05,319 --> 00:18:07,955
First you say it was Jasper.
Now it's the lover that did it.

404
00:18:08,023 --> 00:18:08,958
You gonna make up your mind?

405
00:18:08,959 --> 00:18:10,859
What lover? We understood
she had no social life.

406
00:18:11,626 --> 00:18:12,628
I didn't know she did.

407
00:18:12,629 --> 00:18:16,429
Oh, well, she did, and competent
police would have known that.

408
00:18:16,496 --> 00:18:18,296
Why didn't you tell us
this earlier?

409
00:18:18,364 --> 00:18:21,866
<i>Why don't I just do your job
for you? How would that be?</i>

410
00:18:21,934 --> 00:18:23,901
Oh, just please
arrest her or something.

411
00:18:23,969 --> 00:18:26,169
Nothing to hold her on.

412
00:18:26,237 --> 00:18:28,171
Eh.

413
00:18:28,239 --> 00:18:30,073
Eh.

414
00:18:30,140 --> 00:18:34,376
I'm the rookie on the team.
(chuckles)

415
00:18:34,444 --> 00:18:37,345
Been here... 18 months now.

416
00:18:37,413 --> 00:18:40,782
Um, it's hard work,

417
00:18:40,850 --> 00:18:45,252
but this has been my dream
ever since I was a kid--

418
00:18:45,320 --> 00:18:47,020
to be a Detective.

419
00:18:47,088 --> 00:18:49,889
(mike) And what's been
the most surprising thing

420
00:18:49,957 --> 00:18:52,224
you've learned
about this job you do?

421
00:18:54,627 --> 00:18:56,628
I've...

422
00:18:56,696 --> 00:18:59,698
learned a lot about myself...

423
00:18:59,765 --> 00:19:02,833
As well as about other people--

424
00:19:02,901 --> 00:19:07,303
stuff I wish
I didn't know sometimes.

425
00:19:07,371 --> 00:19:09,305
Stuff like...

426
00:19:09,372 --> 00:19:14,776
Why people do bad things
to one another.

427
00:19:14,844 --> 00:19:17,478
It's mainly because of secrets.

428
00:19:17,546 --> 00:19:20,813
Trying to hide the truth
chips away at your spirit.

429
00:19:20,881 --> 00:19:24,615
Secrets ruin relationships.

430
00:19:24,683 --> 00:19:26,617
We finally got the footage

431
00:19:26,684 --> 00:19:29,618
from every news station covering
the groundbreaking ceremony.

432
00:19:29,686 --> 00:19:31,620
Apparently, threats work.

433
00:19:31,687 --> 00:19:34,121
These are two separate
vantage points of the mayor,

434
00:19:34,189 --> 00:19:37,658
and these are feeds
of the crowd. There--that guy.
(clicking)

435
00:19:37,726 --> 00:19:40,093
(Lisbon)
Can you narrow it down for us?

436
00:19:40,161 --> 00:19:41,362
There's, like, 50 guys there.
The guy in the crowd there--

437
00:19:41,430 --> 00:19:42,767
After the mayor
digs up the victim.

438
00:19:43,168 --> 00:19:47,068
He certainly doesn't look like
he fits in. Oh, that's bold.

439
00:19:47,635 --> 00:19:50,436
A Jasper acolyte.
Or the man himself.

440
00:19:50,503 --> 00:19:53,671
Get with the local P.D.
See if they can identify him.

441
00:19:53,739 --> 00:19:55,672
(clears throat)

442
00:19:55,740 --> 00:19:58,141
(Lisbon) What is it?
Nothing. Just hungry.

443
00:20:07,247 --> 00:20:08,647
So we went back
to St. Clare's apartment,

444
00:20:08,715 --> 00:20:10,617
went through her closet
and realized that some

445
00:20:10,685 --> 00:20:12,186
of her work shirts--
(Jane) button on the right.

446
00:20:12,254 --> 00:20:13,455
Yeah, and not her size.

447
00:20:13,556 --> 00:20:15,656
So the mayor was right.
She did have a lover.

448
00:20:15,723 --> 00:20:16,857
Of course she had a lover.

449
00:20:16,924 --> 00:20:19,259
That necklace she always wore
was obviously a romantic gift.

450
00:20:19,326 --> 00:20:20,862
She'd never spend
that kind of money on herself.

451
00:20:20,863 --> 00:20:23,663
Now you say so.
Very wise in hindsight.

452
00:20:23,830 --> 00:20:25,097
Well, I thought
it went without saying.

453
00:20:25,165 --> 00:20:27,099
It's horribly obvious when
people are in a relationship--

454
00:20:27,167 --> 00:20:29,735
Impossible to hide,
try though they might.

455
00:20:31,202 --> 00:20:32,139
She was
a very attractive woman.

456
00:20:32,206 --> 00:20:35,209
I would not be surprised
if she had two lovers.

457
00:20:35,277 --> 00:20:37,779
There is nothing here.
I'm gonna go out for lunch.

458
00:20:39,847 --> 00:20:42,484
Turn that thing off, or I will
shove it down your throat.

459
00:20:42,552 --> 00:20:44,652
(Lisbon) Let's take a walk,
shall we?

460
00:20:44,720 --> 00:20:46,554
Come on.

461
00:20:57,363 --> 00:20:59,797
I know it hasn't been
the most pleasant experience

462
00:20:59,865 --> 00:21:01,732
having a camera crew here.

463
00:21:01,800 --> 00:21:04,701
But you gotta cooperate--
deputy A.G.'s orders.

464
00:21:04,769 --> 00:21:06,836
Yeah.

465
00:21:06,904 --> 00:21:09,172
So what's the deal?
I would think out of everybody,

466
00:21:09,239 --> 00:21:11,974
you'd be the most comfortable
with the cameras.

467
00:21:14,977 --> 00:21:16,210
Mm.

468
00:21:16,278 --> 00:21:18,612
Last time I was
in front of a camera,

469
00:21:18,680 --> 00:21:22,182
things, uh,
didn't turn out so well.

470
00:21:22,250 --> 00:21:26,018
Oh, God, Jane, I'm sorry.

471
00:21:26,086 --> 00:21:29,888
You don't need to be sorry,
and you're right.

472
00:21:29,956 --> 00:21:34,259
There's no reason not to be
civil. I'm going to apologize.

473
00:21:38,630 --> 00:21:42,566
Hey, I'm sorry.
We didn't mean to be intrusive.

474
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:44,401
No, I-I shouldn't
have snapped at you.

475
00:21:44,469 --> 00:21:48,371
I'm sorry. I just--I don't
like feeling spied on.

476
00:21:48,439 --> 00:21:50,372
It's my own little neurosis.

477
00:21:50,440 --> 00:21:52,374
You're just doing
your job, right?

478
00:21:52,442 --> 00:21:55,210
Right.
Well, let me buy you a taco.

479
00:21:55,278 --> 00:21:57,212
Sure.
I know you're in.

480
00:21:57,280 --> 00:22:01,449
<i>I am kind of hungry.
That's the spirit. I know
the perfect place. Vámonos.</i>

481
00:22:03,819 --> 00:22:07,387
<i>Muchas gracias.</i>

482
00:22:07,455 --> 00:22:10,523
Mike.
Thank you.

483
00:22:10,591 --> 00:22:14,560
Steve. So tell me
about news gathering.

484
00:22:14,628 --> 00:22:17,629
(Steve) You get an assignment,
and pretty much--

485
00:22:17,697 --> 00:22:20,732
Whoa! Whoa!
(crowd gasping and murmuring)

486
00:22:30,042 --> 00:22:33,077
Did you get that?
Did you get it?

487
00:22:33,145 --> 00:22:35,313
(sighs)

488
00:22:38,984 --> 00:22:39,984
Keep moving.

489
00:22:44,985 --> 00:22:46,485
Let's go.

490
00:22:48,785 --> 00:22:53,256
I don't know where we're going,
but I hope there's a bathroom.

491
00:22:53,323 --> 00:22:56,493
I am busting.

492
00:22:56,560 --> 00:22:58,127
Ohh.

493
00:23:03,131 --> 00:23:04,064
Definitely Jasper.

494
00:23:04,132 --> 00:23:05,166
The description of the van

495
00:23:05,234 --> 00:23:06,768
matches one seen
near the condo fire

496
00:23:06,835 --> 00:23:08,669
and the luxury car lot
Jasper destroyed.

497
00:23:08,937 --> 00:23:10,871
How long has Chief Donner
had this information?

498
00:23:10,938 --> 00:23:13,206
Contact the local
and the county P.D.
On it.

499
00:23:13,274 --> 00:23:14,708
We got a hit
on the Jasper associate

500
00:23:14,775 --> 00:23:16,043
at the groundbreaking ceremony.

501
00:23:16,110 --> 00:23:17,511
Local activists
draw the line at kidnapping.

502
00:23:17,579 --> 00:23:18,413
They gave this guy up fast.

503
00:23:18,414 --> 00:23:21,614
Bart Henrik. On his blog, he
calls himself a green warrior.

504
00:23:21,681 --> 00:23:23,915
He's been arrested several times
for inciting a riot,

505
00:23:23,983 --> 00:23:25,585
public disorder and vandalism.

506
00:23:25,786 --> 00:23:28,086
Go find him. Take Rigsby.
You got it.

507
00:23:30,220 --> 00:23:33,388
(crickets chirping)

508
00:23:58,879 --> 00:24:00,279
(clicks)

509
00:24:08,486 --> 00:24:10,020
I can see you mean business.

510
00:24:09,088 --> 00:24:12,656
Uh, there's no need for
firearms. I'm not Harry Houdini.

511
00:24:12,824 --> 00:24:13,757
Quiet.

512
00:24:16,593 --> 00:24:19,227
Thank you.

513
00:24:19,295 --> 00:24:21,362
So you're Jasper.

514
00:24:23,365 --> 00:24:24,998
Well, I'm honored.

515
00:24:27,535 --> 00:24:29,469
Please don't say
you kidnapped me for ransom,

516
00:24:29,537 --> 00:24:33,039
because I-I doubt you'll get
$50, let alone save the whales.

517
00:24:33,107 --> 00:24:36,375
No ransom. In actuality,
just a simple message--

518
00:24:36,443 --> 00:24:38,811
I did not kill
Martha St. Clare

519
00:24:38,878 --> 00:24:41,745
And I didn't throw that
firebomb in Krupp's office.

520
00:24:41,813 --> 00:24:44,814
And you--you are gonna
tell that to the police

521
00:24:44,882 --> 00:24:45,818
And to the media.

522
00:24:45,819 --> 00:24:48,019
So you kidnapped me
to proclaim your innocence.

523
00:24:48,885 --> 00:24:51,253
Have you ever heard
of a phone?

524
00:24:51,321 --> 00:24:53,621
Oh, yeah. I see.

525
00:24:53,689 --> 00:24:56,624
If you kidnap me,
and I pass on the message,

526
00:24:56,692 --> 00:25:00,161
then you get a blast of
that publicity that you love.

527
00:25:00,229 --> 00:25:02,163
If I am branded a killer,

528
00:25:02,231 --> 00:25:04,432
everything I have fought for
is discredited.

529
00:25:04,499 --> 00:25:07,434
People support me because I have
respect for all living things.

530
00:25:07,502 --> 00:25:10,537
Yes. Yes,
it's a good rule of thumb

531
00:25:10,604 --> 00:25:13,172
to avoid doing things
that require you to wear a mask.

532
00:25:13,240 --> 00:25:16,275
And you're
such a handsome fellow, too.

533
00:25:18,177 --> 00:25:21,879
How'd you know
I'm handsome?

534
00:25:21,947 --> 00:25:24,348
Well, I was
just speaking figuratively.

535
00:25:24,416 --> 00:25:26,183
No, you weren't.

536
00:25:26,250 --> 00:25:28,184
You know who I am.

537
00:25:28,252 --> 00:25:30,186
No, I have no idea.

538
00:25:30,254 --> 00:25:32,521
Leave us
and don't come back.

539
00:25:32,589 --> 00:25:35,122
No, he doesn't have to
go anywhere. I-I-I--

540
00:25:35,190 --> 00:25:37,125
Will you listen to me?
I have no idea--

541
00:25:37,193 --> 00:25:41,029
You could be Elvis Presley,
for all I know.
How did you know?

542
00:25:41,096 --> 00:25:43,064
I don't know.
How did you...

543
00:25:43,131 --> 00:25:46,233
Please don't do that.

544
00:25:46,300 --> 00:25:48,034
Pl-- (sighs)

545
00:25:48,101 --> 00:25:50,569
(grunts)

546
00:25:53,105 --> 00:25:57,140
How did you know?

547
00:26:01,110 --> 00:26:04,145
Well, what's not to know?

548
00:26:04,213 --> 00:26:06,780
Your height,
your body language,

549
00:26:06,848 --> 00:26:09,248
Your syntax.

550
00:26:09,316 --> 00:26:10,916
You said "in actuality."

551
00:26:10,984 --> 00:26:13,219
I mean,
who--who says "in actuality"?

552
00:26:14,890 --> 00:26:16,091
Yes.

553
00:26:16,159 --> 00:26:17,793
(whispers) yeah.

554
00:26:17,860 --> 00:26:20,261
Very clever.

555
00:26:21,997 --> 00:26:24,331
So now we have a problem.

556
00:26:34,207 --> 00:26:37,142
Get that thing out of my face!

557
00:26:50,488 --> 00:26:52,989
Jasper kidnapped our colleague.
Where are they?

558
00:26:53,057 --> 00:26:56,793
Jasper who?
Did you know you can get more
time for kidnapping than murder?

559
00:26:56,860 --> 00:26:59,829
That's crazy, right?
And being
an accessory after the fact

560
00:26:59,897 --> 00:27:02,333
makes you just as guilty
as Jasper.

561
00:27:03,902 --> 00:27:07,136
Man, Jasper's avenging
mother earth. That's all.

562
00:27:07,204 --> 00:27:10,139
You know him well enough
to be sure of his motives.
Yes.

563
00:27:10,206 --> 00:27:13,141
You know him so well you can
tell us where he might be.

564
00:27:13,209 --> 00:27:16,877
Even if I knew, which I don't,
I would never betray Jasper.
"never" is a big word.

565
00:27:16,945 --> 00:27:20,280
Try me.
What would Jane want us to do
in this situation, Cho?

566
00:27:20,348 --> 00:27:23,383
With his life in jeopardy?
You know
what he'd want us to do.

567
00:27:23,451 --> 00:27:25,218
Yep. Okay.

568
00:27:25,285 --> 00:27:29,054
(Rigsby)
I guess we have to go there.

569
00:27:33,825 --> 00:27:36,493
We should call an ambulance.
It's procedure.
Sure. They can set it fast,

570
00:27:36,561 --> 00:27:39,862
And we can get straight back
to questioning.
Wait. Set what?

571
00:27:39,930 --> 00:27:41,363
(loud clank)

572
00:27:41,431 --> 00:27:44,166
Your arm--you broke it,
slipped on the stairs.

573
00:27:44,233 --> 00:27:46,301
Yeah, you should
be more careful, Henrik.

574
00:27:46,368 --> 00:27:49,870
Hey. Hey. A bunch of people
saw me come in here fine.

575
00:27:49,938 --> 00:27:51,905
A bunch of cops,
and I'm one of them.

576
00:27:51,973 --> 00:27:53,406
I saw you fall.

577
00:27:53,474 --> 00:27:56,242
And every cop in this building
will say exactly the same.

578
00:27:56,309 --> 00:27:57,976
(thud)

579
00:28:00,580 --> 00:28:03,348
(blinds rattle)

580
00:28:08,153 --> 00:28:10,654
A cabin
in the Sierra foothills,

581
00:28:10,721 --> 00:28:12,655
10 miles
northeast of Salter.

582
00:28:12,723 --> 00:28:14,056
Nice work.

583
00:28:16,159 --> 00:28:17,726
What to do?

584
00:28:17,794 --> 00:28:19,227
What to do?

585
00:28:19,295 --> 00:28:21,729
If I let you go now,
you'll rat me out.

586
00:28:21,797 --> 00:28:23,731
If I may make a suggestion?

587
00:28:23,799 --> 00:28:26,166
No, you may not.

588
00:28:26,234 --> 00:28:28,435
Please, Wilson. I can help.

589
00:28:28,502 --> 00:28:31,904
I cannot go to prison.

590
00:28:31,972 --> 00:28:34,407
I need to finish my work.
Don't you see?

591
00:28:34,474 --> 00:28:37,676
I do. I see.
Your work is very important.

592
00:28:37,743 --> 00:28:39,877
But what I don't understand,
though,

593
00:28:39,945 --> 00:28:43,447
Is why you were working
in the mayor's office.
Where better to study the enemy

594
00:28:43,515 --> 00:28:46,449
than from within their very camp?
Did you know that the mayor

595
00:28:46,517 --> 00:28:49,218
Was taking bribes
from the developer Krupp?

596
00:28:49,286 --> 00:28:51,620
Of course. Who do you think
put Martha onto it?

597
00:28:51,688 --> 00:28:54,956
Ah. You told her.

598
00:28:55,024 --> 00:28:58,793
But why not expose the mayor
yourself or do it as Jasper?

599
00:28:58,860 --> 00:29:01,795
They would know that Jasper was
inside the mayor's office.

600
00:29:01,863 --> 00:29:03,797
They would soon suspect me.

601
00:29:03,864 --> 00:29:05,798
I work in the shadows.

602
00:29:05,866 --> 00:29:08,234
That's why I am still here,
still fighting.

603
00:29:08,301 --> 00:29:10,202
I understand.

604
00:29:10,270 --> 00:29:11,770
Let me help you.

605
00:29:11,838 --> 00:29:14,272
Don't try to play me.

606
00:29:14,340 --> 00:29:18,042
Don't go saying you won't tell
on me if I set you free,

607
00:29:18,109 --> 00:29:20,043
Because I know you will.

608
00:29:20,111 --> 00:29:23,113
Wilson, I am not trying to
play you. I will not play you.

609
00:29:23,180 --> 00:29:27,049
I understand and respect
your intelligence.

610
00:29:27,117 --> 00:29:30,118
Have a seat.

611
00:29:30,186 --> 00:29:31,920
Just take a moment.

612
00:29:41,862 --> 00:29:44,664
(sighs)

613
00:29:47,534 --> 00:29:50,769
Wilson, look at me.

614
00:29:50,837 --> 00:29:52,604
I can help you.

615
00:29:55,340 --> 00:29:56,907
(whispers) how?

616
00:29:56,975 --> 00:30:00,076
Look at me.

617
00:30:00,144 --> 00:30:02,746
You can see
that I'm telling the truth.

618
00:30:04,915 --> 00:30:08,618
I want what you want--

619
00:30:08,685 --> 00:30:11,821
Peace and harmony.

620
00:30:11,888 --> 00:30:14,623
Peace...

621
00:30:14,690 --> 00:30:16,424
Quiet...

622
00:30:18,461 --> 00:30:19,927
It's easy.

623
00:30:19,995 --> 00:30:23,197
You can have it.

624
00:30:25,066 --> 00:30:27,800
If you want it,
you can have it.

625
00:30:29,435 --> 00:30:32,504
So peaceful.

626
00:30:34,440 --> 00:30:38,307
This is Chief Donner of
the Salter Police Department!

627
00:30:38,375 --> 00:30:41,777
You're completely surrounded.
Come out with your hands up!
Stay cool.

628
00:30:53,421 --> 00:30:56,190
Just stay cool.

629
00:31:04,854 --> 00:31:06,554
Clear!

630
00:31:06,622 --> 00:31:07,956
(Rigsby) clear!

631
00:31:08,127 --> 00:31:09,895
(Patrick) I'm good.
I got him. I got him.

632
00:31:09,963 --> 00:31:11,931
Lisbon?
J-Jane.

633
00:31:12,298 --> 00:31:14,233
Wow. I'm impressed.

634
00:31:14,300 --> 00:31:15,268
How the hell did you find me
out here?

635
00:31:15,269 --> 00:31:16,769
Right, because we're lost
without you?

636
00:31:17,236 --> 00:31:20,838
Well, I wouldn't say that,
but I'm still impressed.
Wait. I--don't move.

637
00:31:20,906 --> 00:31:23,207
Ohh.
They could have booby-trapped
the place.

638
00:31:23,274 --> 00:31:24,543
We'll have the bomb squad
take a look at you.

639
00:31:24,544 --> 00:31:26,644
What? (mutters) you're kidding.
You're kidding.

640
00:31:27,511 --> 00:31:29,178
I'm--I'm thankful
and all that,

641
00:31:29,246 --> 00:31:32,181
But just get me out of here,
and I'll tell you the story.
What story?

642
00:31:32,249 --> 00:31:33,748
Ahh.
(handcuffs clatter)

643
00:31:40,988 --> 00:31:42,921
So we know who Jasper is.
Fonteneau.

644
00:31:42,989 --> 00:31:43,657
No trace of him. Slipped right
through the locals' hands.

645
00:31:43,724 --> 00:31:44,959
He's one man,
for crying out loud.

646
00:31:44,960 --> 00:31:46,560
Well, he obviously knows
those woods a lot better.

647
00:31:47,027 --> 00:31:50,427
Jane, enough recovery time.
Tell us about Fonteneau.

648
00:31:50,495 --> 00:31:53,430
What'd he say?
Well, he spouted
a lot of nonsense, denial.

649
00:31:53,498 --> 00:31:54,731
Truth is, he took the job
in the mayor's office

650
00:31:54,799 --> 00:31:57,599
yo plan targeted attacks
on new developments around town.

651
00:31:57,766 --> 00:32:00,067
He and St. Clare became lovers.
Secret boyfriend.

652
00:32:00,135 --> 00:32:02,669
But when St. Clare found out

653
00:32:02,736 --> 00:32:05,871
about Fonteneau's secret life
as Jasper, he killed her for it,

654
00:32:05,939 --> 00:32:08,874
To keep her quiet.
I'll check on the warrant
for Fonteneau's place.

655
00:32:08,942 --> 00:32:11,444
Get everybody briefed,
suited up and ready to roll.

656
00:32:11,445 --> 00:32:13,145
Oh, look
for St. Clare's necklace.

657
00:32:13,211 --> 00:32:14,745
It was a gift from Fonteneau.

658
00:32:14,813 --> 00:32:18,081
(Patrick) my guess--he took it
when he killed her. We need it.

659
00:32:18,149 --> 00:32:22,618
You guys sit on the location
until the warrant comes in.

660
00:32:22,686 --> 00:32:24,620
Chief Donner?
Yeah, I-it's Lisbon.

661
00:32:24,688 --> 00:32:26,788
Oh, I need some aspirin.

662
00:32:26,856 --> 00:32:29,190
Yeah.
(pills rattle)

663
00:32:29,258 --> 00:32:32,026
Yeah, I-I just wanted--
could you hold on, chief?

664
00:32:32,094 --> 00:32:34,461
Look, that's enough, guys.
We're done filming.

665
00:32:34,529 --> 00:32:36,463
You know,
catching the bad guy would be

666
00:32:36,530 --> 00:32:39,732
A great end of the show, make
you guys look like superstars.

667
00:32:39,800 --> 00:32:42,701
Well, it'd certainly make
the deputy A.G. Very happy.

668
00:32:42,768 --> 00:32:44,635
True.

669
00:32:44,703 --> 00:32:46,769
All right.
You can film the bust,

670
00:32:46,837 --> 00:32:49,138
But you have to do
exactly what I say.

671
00:32:49,205 --> 00:32:51,773
Deal.
Meet me at Fonteneau's
at 0600 hours.

672
00:32:51,841 --> 00:32:54,341
Yes, ma'am.
Hey. Chief,
we're gonna need assistance

673
00:32:54,409 --> 00:32:57,378
from your entry team again.

674
00:33:46,089 --> 00:33:47,789
What now?

675
00:33:47,857 --> 00:33:50,956
We set a perimeter
and wait for the warrant.

676
00:33:51,024 --> 00:33:53,425
Yeah, there's a lot
of this kind of stuff.

677
00:33:53,493 --> 00:33:56,461
Not too many car chases.

678
00:33:56,529 --> 00:34:00,865
Maybe we could, uh, ask a few
questions while we're waiting?

679
00:34:00,933 --> 00:34:04,602
Uh...

680
00:34:04,670 --> 00:34:06,804
Sure. If you must.

681
00:34:09,340 --> 00:34:10,740
(clears throat)

682
00:34:10,808 --> 00:34:14,810
Um, how did you come
to work with the CBI?

683
00:34:14,878 --> 00:34:17,779
You know how.
Yes, but I-I need you
to say it to the camera.

684
00:34:17,847 --> 00:34:21,482
Yeah, yeah. I-I see.
I got it.

685
00:34:21,550 --> 00:34:23,216
(sighs deeply)

686
00:34:23,284 --> 00:34:25,419
Um...

687
00:34:25,486 --> 00:34:27,753
Well, I came to work
with the CBI

688
00:34:27,821 --> 00:34:30,389
After my wife and child
were murdered.

689
00:34:41,832 --> 00:34:44,767
Have you ever experienced
loss like that?

690
00:34:44,834 --> 00:34:46,968
A loss of love?

691
00:34:50,172 --> 00:34:52,839
There's nothing more important
than love, is there?

692
00:34:52,907 --> 00:34:54,841
Well,
we're talking about you.

693
00:34:54,909 --> 00:34:56,376
Yeah.

694
00:34:59,447 --> 00:35:01,881
It can be very hard
when love goes away.

695
00:35:01,949 --> 00:35:05,951
It's like a... A betrayal,

696
00:35:06,018 --> 00:35:09,387
Almost like a violent act,
right?

697
00:35:09,455 --> 00:35:11,856
Right?

698
00:35:11,924 --> 00:35:13,324
I guess.

699
00:35:13,392 --> 00:35:15,826
Um, why don't--why don't
we go back to, um--

700
00:35:15,894 --> 00:35:18,829
When you give someone your heart
and they throw it aside,

701
00:35:18,897 --> 00:35:21,998
It's natural to be angry.

702
00:35:22,066 --> 00:35:24,934
Especially when you've come
to rely on them,

703
00:35:25,002 --> 00:35:28,103
When your career is tied
to theirs.

704
00:35:28,171 --> 00:35:30,739
I don't know what you're,
uh--

705
00:35:30,806 --> 00:35:33,741
Why don't you show us
what you got in your pockets?
What?

706
00:35:33,809 --> 00:35:35,443
You heard me.
No.

707
00:35:35,510 --> 00:35:36,911
Why not?

708
00:35:36,978 --> 00:35:40,080
Because you don't have
the right.

709
00:35:40,148 --> 00:35:42,416
Okay.

710
00:35:42,483 --> 00:35:45,418
Okay. I'll tell you
what you have in your pocket,

711
00:35:45,486 --> 00:35:47,420
And you tell me if I'm right.

712
00:35:47,488 --> 00:35:49,922
In your pocket, you have
a blue topaz necklace

713
00:35:49,990 --> 00:35:52,857
that you once gave
to Martha St. Clare

714
00:35:52,925 --> 00:35:54,359
when you were lovers.

715
00:35:54,427 --> 00:35:56,894
You took that necklace back
after you killed her.

716
00:35:56,962 --> 00:35:59,931
You were gonna plant it
in Fonteneau's house,

717
00:35:59,998 --> 00:36:02,499
Prompted by
my cunningly brilliant ruse.

718
00:36:06,504 --> 00:36:09,604
Aha.

719
00:36:09,672 --> 00:36:12,440
Aha. That's it.

720
00:36:12,508 --> 00:36:14,875
I don't know
how that got in there.

721
00:36:14,943 --> 00:36:17,811
Oh, please. Don't be so silly.
Arrest him, Cho.

722
00:36:17,879 --> 00:36:20,414
Get on your knees.
Put your hands on your head.

723
00:36:20,482 --> 00:36:21,882
Now!

724
00:36:23,384 --> 00:36:24,551
(click)

725
00:36:24,618 --> 00:36:26,918
Get up.

726
00:36:26,986 --> 00:36:29,420
That's for you.

727
00:36:29,488 --> 00:36:30,921
And this...

728
00:36:32,991 --> 00:36:34,491
Is for me.

729
00:36:38,462 --> 00:36:41,364
Here it comes.

730
00:36:42,699 --> 00:36:45,299
Bang. There.
You looked away.

731
00:36:45,367 --> 00:36:47,534
Martha St. Clare's body
hasn't been revealed,

732
00:36:47,602 --> 00:36:50,537
And you looked away, because you
knew what was gonna happen,

733
00:36:50,605 --> 00:36:53,039
Because you buried that body
at that building site

734
00:36:53,107 --> 00:36:56,775
and you firebombed the trailer
to try and frame Jasper.

735
00:36:56,843 --> 00:37:00,011
You're too clever, Mike,
you're just too clever.

736
00:37:00,078 --> 00:37:03,013
Nah.
You spout a lot of theory,

737
00:37:03,081 --> 00:37:05,448
But no legal proof.
Ah.

738
00:37:05,516 --> 00:37:08,717
You want legal proof?
The lab reports came back.

739
00:37:08,785 --> 00:37:11,787
They found traces of Martha's
blood in the trunk of your car.

740
00:37:14,391 --> 00:37:16,889
Do you want to tell us
what happened?

741
00:37:25,231 --> 00:37:28,466
Rumors said
the mayor was dirty,

742
00:37:28,534 --> 00:37:30,902
But there was no proof.

743
00:37:30,969 --> 00:37:32,903
I knew something was up.

744
00:37:32,971 --> 00:37:36,705
But... no matter
how much I pushed her,

745
00:37:36,773 --> 00:37:40,210
Martha wouldn't say anything.
Nothing.

746
00:37:42,113 --> 00:37:44,846
And last night,

747
00:37:44,913 --> 00:37:47,047
<i>I was going through
her computer,</i>

748
00:37:47,115 --> 00:37:49,852
<i>Just checking on some stuff,
you know?</i>

749
00:37:51,555 --> 00:37:55,391
<i>I found this speech
she was preparing to give,</i>

750
00:37:55,459 --> 00:37:58,327
<i>Exposing the mayor
as corrupt,</i>

751
00:37:58,395 --> 00:37:59,828
With proof--

752
00:37:59,895 --> 00:38:01,993
Facts and figures,
the whole deal.

753
00:38:02,061 --> 00:38:05,329
<i>And she kept it from me
the whole time.</i>

754
00:38:05,397 --> 00:38:08,364
This is a story that could have
made my career.

755
00:38:08,432 --> 00:38:11,967
I have been waiting
for a story like this

756
00:38:12,035 --> 00:38:13,635
My whole life.

757
00:38:13,703 --> 00:38:16,704
<i>And she's mad 'cause I'm
on her computer. Hello.</i>

758
00:38:16,772 --> 00:38:19,540
<i>So she...</i>

759
00:38:19,608 --> 00:38:24,311
She said, uh, she couldn't trust
me anymore and that it was over.

760
00:38:24,378 --> 00:38:27,346
<i>The argument escalated,</i>

761
00:38:27,414 --> 00:38:30,048
<i>And, uh,
I took my necklace back.</i>

762
00:38:30,116 --> 00:38:33,084
<i>And then she starts
taunting me,</i>

763
00:38:33,152 --> 00:38:36,388
<i>You know, implying that
I don't have what it takes</i>

764
00:38:36,456 --> 00:38:39,424
<i>To be in the big leagues
anyway,</i>

765
00:38:39,492 --> 00:38:41,860
<i>Saying I'm a loser.</i>

766
00:38:41,927 --> 00:38:44,262
She's had enough?

767
00:38:44,329 --> 00:38:47,231
<i>She's had enough? She has?</i>

768
00:38:47,299 --> 00:38:48,799
No, no, no, no.

769
00:38:48,867 --> 00:38:50,333
I've had enough.

770
00:38:50,401 --> 00:38:53,102
Me!

771
00:38:58,841 --> 00:39:01,409
Well...

772
00:39:01,477 --> 00:39:03,911
We'll take that
as a confession.

773
00:39:03,979 --> 00:39:07,047
<i>In a stunning revelation,
mayor Melba Walker Shannon</i>

774
00:39:07,115 --> 00:39:10,050
<i>Has been arrested by the D.A.
for corruption charges...
(Rigsby) oh, yeah.</i>

775
00:39:10,118 --> 00:39:12,552
<i>Stemming from the Granton
at Salter development.</i>

776
00:39:12,620 --> 00:39:15,522
<i>The accuser is her
closest aide, Wilson Fonteneau,</i>

777
00:39:15,590 --> 00:39:17,524
<i>who agreed to testify
against the mayor</i>

778
00:39:17,591 --> 00:39:19,025
<i>in exchange for leniency</i>

779
00:39:19,093 --> 00:39:22,895
<i>Regarding his activities
as eco-terrorist "Jasper."</i>

780
00:39:22,962 --> 00:39:25,263
<i>This only
the latest development</i>

781
00:39:25,331 --> 00:39:27,899
<i>In a bizarre story
of murder and greed</i>

782
00:39:27,966 --> 00:39:31,902
<i>That has captivated
the central valley.
Hey. I was enjoying that.</i>

783
00:39:31,970 --> 00:39:34,738
Ugh. I hate how they
overdramatize everything.
Yeah, I hate that.

784
00:39:34,805 --> 00:39:36,740
(deepens voice)
"captured the central valley."

785
00:39:36,807 --> 00:39:39,208
(normal voice) give me a break.
Doughnuts.

786
00:39:39,276 --> 00:39:41,844
Thanks.
Ladies first.

787
00:39:41,912 --> 00:39:44,179
So, uh, guys?

788
00:39:44,247 --> 00:39:47,248
Uh, I have something to say.

789
00:39:47,316 --> 00:39:49,984
<i>We have something to say.</i>

790
00:39:53,921 --> 00:39:55,221
Uh, life's too short
for dishonesty Van Pelt--

791
00:39:55,289 --> 00:39:57,723
Grace and I are... Lovers.

792
00:40:01,394 --> 00:40:03,528
No, you're not.

793
00:40:03,596 --> 00:40:05,129
Um, yes, we are.

794
00:40:05,197 --> 00:40:08,165
No, you are not lovers.

795
00:40:08,233 --> 00:40:12,402
Uh, but we are, though.
No, you're not,
because a sexual relationship

796
00:40:12,470 --> 00:40:15,671
between two fellow
bureau employees is

797
00:40:15,739 --> 00:40:18,307
Strictly against the rules.

798
00:40:18,374 --> 00:40:20,308
Which is why we kept it
a secret.

799
00:40:20,376 --> 00:40:22,810
But we don't want to live
a lie anymore.

800
00:40:22,878 --> 00:40:24,746
(inhales deeply)
come what may.

801
00:40:24,813 --> 00:40:26,181
(chuckles)

802
00:40:27,749 --> 00:40:30,351
Well, it's a big secret.
Well-kept.

803
00:40:30,418 --> 00:40:32,452
Well, maybe you knew,
but nobody else did.

804
00:40:32,520 --> 00:40:34,821
I knew. Half the building knows.
They do not.

805
00:40:34,888 --> 00:40:37,823
The only person that didn't know
is glaring at you right now.

806
00:40:37,890 --> 00:40:40,859
And now I have to do
something about it.

807
00:40:40,926 --> 00:40:43,595
<i>What are you gonna do?
Yeah, what are you gonna do?</i>

808
00:40:47,700 --> 00:40:49,934
I'm thinking.

809
00:40:50,002 --> 00:41:06,648
(Lisbon)
Go.

